<P>In one part of the poem, Prodicus's apologue, of Hercules meeting VIRTUE and PLEASURE, is introduced. In the &s;peech of PLEASURE, our author changes his metre; and breaks forth into a lyrical &s;train, not totally void of elegance and delicacy, and in a rhythmical arrangement adopted by Gray.</P>
