<P>The poem called the BOUGE OF COURT, or the <HI>Rewards of a Court,</HI> is in the manner of a pageaunt, con&s;i&s;ting of &s;even per&s;onifications. Here our author, in adopting the more grave and &s;tately movement of the &s;even lined &s;tanza <NOTE N="e" PLACE="foot">But in this &s;tanza he &s;ometimes relap&s;es into the ab&s;urdities of his favorite &s;tyle of compo&s;ition. For in&s;tance, in SPEAKE PARROT, p. 97.
<Q><LG>
