<P>Pag. 73. to l. 21. ADD this Note, <Q REND="inline">"The rhymes here called, by Robert de Brunne, <HI>Couw&eacute;e,</HI> and <HI>Enterlac&eacute;e,</HI> were undoubtedly derived from the Latin rhymers of that age, who u&s;ed ver&s;us <HI>caudati</HI> et <HI>interlaqueati.</HI> Brunne here profe&s;&s;es to avoid the&s;e elegancies of compo&s;ition, yet he has intermixed many pa&s;&s;ages in <HI>Rime Couw&eacute;e.</HI> See his CHRONICLE, p. 266. 273. &amp;c. &amp;c. And almo&s;t all the latter part of his work from the Conque&s;t is written in rhyme <HI>enterlac&eacute;e,</HI> each couplet rhyming in the middle, as well as the end. As thus, MSS. HARL. 1002.</Q></P>
<P>Plau&s;us Graecorum &verbar; lux caecis et via claudis &verbar; Incola caelorum &verbar; virgo digni&s;&s;ima laudis.</P>
<P>The rhyme <HI>Ba&s;ton</HI> had its appellation from Robert Ba&s;ton, a celebrated Latin rhymer about the year 1315. The rhyme <HI>&s;trangere</HI> means <HI>uncommon.</HI> See CANTERBURY TALES, vol. 4. p. 72. &s;eq. ut infr. The reader, curious on this &s;ubject, may receive further information from a manu&s;cript in the Bodleian library, in which are &s;pecimens of METRA <HI>Leonina, cri&s;tata, cornuta, recriproca,</HI> &amp;c. MSS. LAUD. K. 3. 4^t^o. In the &s;ame library, there is a very antient manu&s;cript copy of Aldhelm's Latin poem <HI>De Virginitate et Laude Sanctorum,</HI> written about the year 700, and given by Thomas Allen, with Saxon glo&s;&s;es, and the text almo&s;t in &s;emi-&s;axon characters. The&s;e are the two fir&s;t ver&s;es.
<Q><L>Metrica tyrones nunc promant carmina ca&s;ti,</L>
