<P>Pag. 197. to l. 15. ADD this Note; <Q REND="inline">"I know not if by <HI>&s;ire Jovyn</HI> he means Jupiter, or the Roman emperour called Jovinian, again&s;t whom &s;aint Jerom wrote, and who&s;e hi&s;tory is in the GESTA ROMANORUM, c. 59. He is mentioned by Chaucer as an example of pride, luxury, and lu&s;t. SOMP. T. v. 7511. Verdier (in V.) recites a <HI>Moralite</HI> on Jovinian, with nineteen characters, printed at Lyons, from an antient copy in 1581, 8^v^o. With the title <HI>L'Orgueil et pre&s;omption de l'Empereur</HI> JOVI|NIAN. But <HI>Jovyn</HI> being mentioned here with <HI>Plotoun</HI> and <HI>Apol|lin,</HI> &s;eems to mean <HI>Jove</HI> or <HI>Jupiter;</HI> and the appellation, SIRE, perhaps implies <HI>father,</HI> or <HI>chief,</HI> of the heathen gods.</Q></P>
