the trees felled for the pyre, with the con&s;ternation of the Nymphs, takes up more than twenty-four lines. v. 84.&mdash;116. In Chaucer about thirteen, v. 2922.&mdash;2937. In Boccacio, &s;ix &s;tanzas. B. xi. Of the three poets, Statius is mo&s;t reprehen|&s;ible, the fir&s;t author of this ill-placed and unnece&s;&s;ary de&s;crip|tion, and who did not live in a Gothic age. The &s;tatues of Mars and Venus I imagined had been copied from Fulgentius, Boccacio's favorite mythographer. But Fulgentius &s;ays no|thing of Mars: and of Venus, that &s;he only &s;tood in the &s;ea on a couch, attended by the Graces. It is from Statius that The|&s;eus became a hero of romance.</P>
